With the recent growth of phylogenetics, this classification is no longer viable. The basic rhachitomous condition is found in many primitive tetrapods, and is not unique to one group of temnospondyls. Moreover, the distinction between rhachitomous and stereospondylous temnospondyls is based on a single character, a condition that is known to be labile in the group. After phylogenetic studies based on a number of characters were published, temnospondyls were shown to be a natural grade of primitive tetrapods, and form a single monophyletic group with which no other tetrapods are closely related.
